<span key="42d311d5a6e34fd09116c93294f68664"><span offset-key="42d311d5a6e34fd09116c93294f68664:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/elasticbeanstalk/" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="e526865cffc7478bb8e3014ed9839635" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-68155_259-68156-237__"><span data-key="0e58928fb3594b71aa689b0473be08b8"><span data-offset-key="0e58928fb3594b71aa689b0473be08b8:0">Elastic Beanstalk</span></span></span></a><span key="8f665738599644089b1f9a280df0442d"><span offset-key="8f665738599644089b1f9a280df0442d:0"> is a </span></span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platform_as_a_service" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="c0fb432e330a4a67978ebf6a8ff3122f" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-68155_259-68156-237__"><span data-key="0dfb29d697f0492dbca3c3756b5a7e47"><span data-offset-key="0dfb29d697f0492dbca3c3756b5a7e47:0">PaaS</span></span></span></a><span key="1a09869ab6ba4db3a0bfffb7567043f7"><span offset-key="1a09869ab6ba4db3a0bfffb7567043f7:0"> service that is used in Labs to host Data Science related APIs.</span></span>

## 

<span key="ab6bf5eb1d244009b174a38bfc7ecdef"><span offset-key="ab6bf5eb1d244009b174a38bfc7ecdef:0">FAQ</span></span>

<span key="9aa84992260948f8a7b550254b2059bd">**Why does my Elastic Beanstalk application fail with permission denied, mkdir?**</span>

<span key="0f6125ae73b34517a315518dd55e4bf9"><span offset-key="0f6125ae73b34517a315518dd55e4bf9:0">This is caused by the following:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9260815371d6430f89bf058b3ba19f18"><span offset-key="9260815371d6430f89bf058b3ba19f18:0">AWS Beanstalk servers are based on Amazon Linux, now you know</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="ab4b13a2730c48368f59c9810f62cd54"><span offset-key="ab4b13a2730c48368f59c9810f62cd54:0">The node-gyp module has native code, so needs to be compiled, no big deal</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="ec2055a0774d4e81b15c3e5f2574582b"><span offset-key="ec2055a0774d4e81b15c3e5f2574582b:0">There is no node-gyp binary distribution for Amazon Linux, it would be nice</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="c0e51e56ef27423fb44ae9d0d6521161"><span offset-key="c0e51e56ef27423fb44ae9d0d6521161:0">NPM tries to build the package on the Beanstalk server, which is normal</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="d3754cd5f0d64e93afe14e93c4534e4c"><span offset-key="d3754cd5f0d64e93afe14e93c4534e4c:0">Part of the build process runs as a non-root user and tries to write to /tmp which is owned by root, seems odd, but okay</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="0d516621c36f4440ad40470944fb3ad9"><span offset-key="0d516621c36f4440ad40470944fb3ad9:0">This mkdir call fails with permission denied and the build fails, which is the correct error</span></span>

<span key="8356d8524b234059a2fe7483c9167621"><span offset-key="8356d8524b234059a2fe7483c9167621:0">There are lots of different solutions on the world wide web, but only one seems to work consistently and is only mildly intrusive:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="74fc746aa1c643ea8e7313ad39f832da"><span offset-key="74fc746aa1c643ea8e7313ad39f832da:0">Go to your Elastic Beanstalk environment</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="53ebefb426e74ff8a3ce757bb3cc77c4"><span offset-key="53ebefb426e74ff8a3ce757bb3cc77c4:0">Click 'Configuration' then click 'Software'</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9bc474974b7c4343a16e64f8bb8fa243"><span offset-key="9bc474974b7c4343a16e64f8bb8fa243:0">At the bottom of this form, add this environment variable:</span></span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="cad13b0985174ec9b0c39abc5fdd256c"><span offset-key="cad13b0985174ec9b0c39abc5fdd256c:0">NPM\_CONFIG\_UNSAFE\_PERM=true</span></span>

        <span key="5d8170031ab44b269177bbd036e0b735"><span offset-key="5d8170031ab44b269177bbd036e0b735:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><span slate-void="true" key="d6f70d77437f4025b9886250e901d408"></span>
        <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1rasi3h" />

        <span key="60205f96831f4e4e8c6eaa101d63f5a2"><span offset-key="60205f96831f4e4e8c6eaa101d63f5a2:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="92e5f8e0626f4227a59fb54228a5960a"><span offset-key="92e5f8e0626f4227a59fb54228a5960a:0">Click 'Apply'</span></span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="c3a3eeac33f24816bf17057d3ccabe37"><span offset-key="c3a3eeac33f24816bf17057d3ccabe37:0">This should trigger a rebuild, which should get you past the issue</span></span>

### 

<span key="79d0c728aa07412aa65699ac49bee6f0"><span offset-key="79d0c728aa07412aa65699ac49bee6f0:0">Application</span></span>

<span key="c2d67eee97714297ba6b914d21af0942"><span offset-key="c2d67eee97714297ba6b914d21af0942:0">An Application in AWS Elastic Beanstalk is simply a collection of Elastic Beanstalk environments. It's simply a mechanism to organize Elastic Beanstalk environments.</span></span>

<span key="6c05cf9841c04682abccdb49c5360ad4"><span offset-key="6c05cf9841c04682abccdb49c5360ad4:0">In Labs, we use Elastic Beanstalk applications to group environments for a specific cohort. See the </span></span><a href="https://docs.labs.lambdaschool.com/standards/infrastructure/aws#aw-200-resource-naming" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="560009eea01e43c88fe7d5fc6edc257c" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-68155_259-68156-237__"><span data-key="800a84cbd0e848bdbaa1e85a0759edff"><span data-offset-key="800a84cbd0e848bdbaa1e85a0759edff:0">Labs Engineering Standards</span></span></span></a><span key="0021327e0715476dbcea8969af8e22af"><span offset-key="0021327e0715476dbcea8969af8e22af:0"> for instructions on how to name an Elastic Beanstalk Application.</span></span>

### 

<span key="359aa863e99c409984c29d9fc79bdd65"><span offset-key="359aa863e99c409984c29d9fc79bdd65:0">Environment</span></span>

<span key="03a2cbabdec94c97ba399a88fca8c926"><span offset-key="03a2cbabdec94c97ba399a88fca8c926:0">An Environment in AWS Elastic Beanstalk is a collection of AWS resources that are managed by the Elastic Beanstalk service.</span></span>

<span key="ed57734dd31649cca134cc311a5d9a73"><span offset-key="ed57734dd31649cca134cc311a5d9a73:0">In Labs, a project team will each have a dedicated environment to host the resources they need for their API. See the </span></span><a href="https://docs.labs.lambdaschool.com/standards/infrastructure/aws#aw-200-resource-naming" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="c880555d5ed34e01bad60cc1fe19ec1f" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-68155_259-68156-237__"><span data-key="569f2463170a4eb4b7af9ff897c17972"><span data-offset-key="569f2463170a4eb4b7af9ff897c17972:0">Labs Engineering Standards</span></span></span></a><span key="d76ede9a18d04be6b49a6c7fc6f6e7f6"><span offset-key="d76ede9a18d04be6b49a6c7fc6f6e7f6:0"> for instructions on how to name an Elastic Beanstalk Environment.</span></span>
